name: david friedberg
tweet: best solution to test for active infection may NOT be PCR. PCR is best CURRENT solution - costs $6, but requires central lab, 6 step procedure, 45 minutes, and requires people, swabs, and reagents. can we get cheap/fast at-home active infection test? yes, we should, soon...

name: david friedberg
tweet: how do we test everyone? we need to test active infection (RNA) AND past infection (antibodies) cheap/quick to really trace/track. antibody tests now getting approved & coming to market (yay!).. these are cheap (<$10) easy-to-use (finger prick at-home) & fast (10mins)...

name: david friedberg
tweet: for factory/worksite/point-of-care applications, the limitation of 10 tests/hr and $40+/test seems like a big hurdle to overcome - you can't test 2,500 ppl working in a single facility with those metrics. seems more of an edge-case solution than a natl everyone tested solution.

name: david friedberg
tweet: you would need to pool all devices centrally + run 24 hours + would still need to solve last-mile problem (more HCWs, PPE, & swabs) to meaningfully move the needle on natl capacity, and cost would likely be 10x a scaled high-throughput multiplexed PCR testing approach

name: david friedberg
tweet: i’ve said it publicly before - the world runs on a 30-day food supply. if the system of food production grinds to a halt, we’re in trouble.. there’s only 30 days of food based on current calories consumed per day. it’s never been considered a relevant stat before

name: david friedberg
tweet: such a model can take in not just pos test result data (biased, delayed, and only partially reported) but can include ICU beds available, broad gen pop antibody testing data, flu symptom reporting data etc. and adjust based on actual data that can have major effects on forecasts

name: david friedberg
tweet: some gov agency or private party should be publishing a continuous model that produces a simulation of covid outbreak prediction scenarios (and associated probability of each) using new data every day

name: david friedberg
tweet: such models are often viewed as deterministic (this is what’s going to happen) and only at a point in time (the forecast doesn’t change). the reality is these models are probabilistic (create a range of different outcomes) and are dynamic (change all the time with new data)

name: david friedberg
tweet: the imperial college model should not be treated as a static predictor.. it uses a range of assumptions and doesn’t have other potentially important variables

name: david friedberg
tweet: there are other variables that aren’t modeled like distribution of A1c, which may be a key driver of outcome/severity in covid-19 ( https://twitter.com/davidasinclair/status/1238972082756648960?s=21 …)

name: david friedberg
tweet: it also highlights that certain assumptions, like R0 can have a massively varied outcome, and it doesn’t clearly adjust asymptomatic patient %ile, which we also don’t clearly know and could also massively change outcomes

name: david friedberg
tweet: the imperial college paper ( https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf …) provides a rather bleak outlook, scenario analysis, and mitigation techniques that seem reasonable based on the modeled outlook

name: david friedberg
tweet: if you work in finance, one way to relate is that these models behave like a DCF model.. if you make slight changes in the terminal growth rate or WACC, you can multiply valuations or reduce them to fractions

name: david friedberg
tweet: nasim taleb highlights how sensitive epidemiological models are to slight changes in variables... you can produce massively divergent outcomes https://twitter.com/nntaleb/status/1239171413342289921?s=21 …

name: david friedberg
tweet: given the possibility of efficacy and the scale of the covid-19 pandemic, this drug should be immediately scaled in production and made broadly available under a right-to-try mandate .. let doctors and patients decide

name: david friedberg
tweet: remdesivir, another promising antiviral, is also not widely available and is only available to patients in the US under a compassionate use application..

name: david friedberg
tweet: the CDC/FDA should let doctors and patients decide if they want to use these drugs and ensure their broad availability (several care providers have told me they can not get prescriptions for chloroquine filled in the bay area)

name: david friedberg
tweet: in the absence of any treatment alternative whatsoever, the CDC should consider making the reco to care providers to consider the Korea protocol in treatment..and make supplies of chloroquine + Kaletra antivirals widely available through mandates to producers & distributors asap

name: david friedberg
tweet: currently, the CDC website ( https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/clinical-guidance-management-patients.html …) tells care providers there is no known treatment ... there is no mention of chloroquine or kaletra (antiviral used in korea)

name: david friedberg
tweet: chloroquine, especially, is a well-studied drug and has a known safety profile. the apparent efficacy and adoption of its use in china, korea, and italy suggests we should consider it for treatment in the US. we don’t recommend it bc we haven’t conducted blinded clinical trials

name: david friedberg
tweet: chloroquine’s apparent efficacy is highlighted in several papers:  https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/bst/14/1/14_2020.01047/_article … https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0924857920300662?via%3Dihub …

name: david friedberg
tweet: as a result of widespread testing, containment, and the adoption of their treatment protocol, south korea is seeing the lowest fatality rate of any country with major outbreak  https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/

name: david friedberg
tweet: we should also be optimistic on treatment for covid-19. korean doctors created a protocol for treatment using antivirals and chloroquine, drugs which are widely available and affordable.  https://www.elsevier.com/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/988648/COVID-19-Drug-Therapy_Mar-2020.pdf …

name: david friedberg
tweet: to be clear, i am NOT anti-containment. i am simply optimistic and try to be data-driven. i want us all to ask questions and answer them with data and facts. everyone freaking out and spiraling and spinning anecdote into fact is generally just bad
